                                <p>
                                    Dear Delegates,
                                </p>
                                <p>As the chairperson of the Special Political and Decolonization Committee, it is my distinct pleasure to welcome you to the 10th stimulation of Doon School Model United Nations. My name is Saksham Goel and I am in the final year of my school life at Doon and am pursuing the ISC curriculum. I have been involved in MUNs for the past three years and have attended several national and international conferences. Aside from MUN, I have keen interests in politics, football and economics.</p>
                                <p>As far as the committee is concerned, SPECPOL is the Fourth Committee of the UN General Assembly. While SPECPOL was derived from the Disarmament and International Security Committee, it takes on issues that the First Committee does not address, as well as looking at topics with a wider scope. Unlike other UN committees, SPECPOL shines a spotlight on issues pertaining to occupation, colonization, and subjugation, with the primary goal of making all countries independent and self-sufficient from outside powers and it also discusses the matters of self-determination, decolonization, and peacekeeping.</p>
                                <p>Being the chairperson of such a highly consequential committee, I hope to effectively create an ethos of conflict, debate and high diplomatic rigour. The decisions you make as a committee could determine the future trajectory of the world map, therefore the participation of all countries is required and it is a must for all the delegates to stick to their foreign and domestic policies.</p>
                                <p>This year, the agendas that will be adressed in SPECPOL are:</p>
                                <p><ul><li><b>The Kurdistan Question</b></li><li><b>Establihment of a Permanent Government in Tibet</b></li></ul></p>
                                <p>With that I bid you good luck and hope to see you at Chandbagh this fall.</p>
