                          <h2>Introduction to Agenda</h2>
                          <div class="divide20"></div>
                          <h3>Agenda 1: Establishing a Permanent Government in Tibet</h3>
                          <p>Tibet is under the clout of two sets of authorities – Tibetan Autonomous region under the People’s Republic of China (PRC) and the government in exile (Central Tibetan Administration) whose nerve centre lies in Dharamsala in India. The Central Tibetan Administration views PRC’s rule with condemnation and calls it colonial and illegitimate and states that PRC is led solely by motive to bolster its own strategic position and obtain natural resources available with Tibet. The PRC argues that historically Tibet was under the territory of China. Hostilities between these two blocks are on the rise, people seem to be unresponsive and there seems to be no clear indication in favour of these two governments. Upholding peace and sovereignty of nations and protecting the interests and rights of the people, this is where the United Nations has to intervene. It lies with the SPECPOL to formulate policies and plans to establish a permanent government in Tibet and effectively mitigating hostilities between the authorities.</p>
                          <h3>Agenda 2: The Question of Kurdistan</h3>
                          <p>Kurdistan essentially comprises south-eastern Turkey, northern Syria, northern Iraq and north-western Iran. The Kurds represent one of the largest Middle Eastern ethnicities and are demanding an independent nation. After the first Iraqi war, the United Nations established a safe-zone in northern Iraq, which became an autonomous Kurdish region. The middle-eastern countries look at an independent Kurdistan as a deplorable threat to their territorial integrity. There is deep-seated hostility between the Middle-eastern states and the countries’ Kurds and the question of granting independence to Kurdistan cannot be left unheeded for long. With United States and the West trying to help the Kurds, there is a risk for an all-out war in the Middle-east. Will the Middle-eastern countries willingly give up their territories? Do the Kurds deserve to get a separate nation? How will the principles of self-determination and statehood play out? It remains with SPECPOL to decide the fate of Kurdistan. </p>
